# Set Up Async Job Processing

## Arguments
- `service`: Service name
- `jobs`: Comma-separated job names to create (e.g., `send-email,generate-report`)

## Architecture

```
API Handler → worker.enqueue('send-email', payload)
                           ↓
                    JobStore (queue)
                           ↓
              JobWorker poll loop (1s interval)
                           ↓
               JobDefinition.handler(payload, ctx)
                   ↓ success           ↓ failure
              status: completed    retry with backoff
                                   (up to maxRetries)
```

## Steps

### 1. Add Dependencies
- Add `@ironplate/jobs` to `apps/{service}/package.json`
- Run `{{ .Project.Spec.Monorepo.PackageManager }} install`

### 2. Define Jobs

```typescript
import type { JobDefinition } from '@ironplate/jobs';

export const sendEmailJob: JobDefinition<{ to: string; subject: string; body: string }> = {
  name: 'send-email',
  maxRetries: 3,
  retryDelayMs: 2000,
  timeoutMs: 30_000,
  handler: async (payload, ctx) => {
    ctx.logger.info({ to: payload.to }, 'Sending email');

    // Check if job was cancelled
    if (ctx.signal.aborted) return;

    await emailService.send(payload);
    ctx.logger.info({ to: payload.to }, 'Email sent');
  },
};

export const generateReportJob: JobDefinition<{ reportId: string; format: string }> = {
  name: 'generate-report',
  maxRetries: 2,
  timeoutMs: 120_000, // 2 minutes
  handler: async (payload, ctx) => {
    ctx.logger.info({ reportId: payload.reportId }, 'Generating report');
    const report = await reportService.generate(payload.reportId, payload.format);
    return { url: report.url };
  },
};
```

### 3. Create Worker

```typescript
import { JobWorker, MemoryJobStore } from '@ironplate/jobs';
import { sendEmailJob, generateReportJob } from './jobs';

// Use MemoryJobStore for development (swap for Redis/DB store in production)
const store = new MemoryJobStore();

export const worker = new JobWorker(store, {
  pollIntervalMs: 1000,
});

worker
  .register(sendEmailJob)
  .register(generateReportJob);
```

### 4. Enqueue Jobs from API Routes

```typescript
import { worker } from '../worker';
import { Router } from 'express';

const router = Router();

router.post('/users/:id/welcome-email', async (req, res) => {
  const jobId = await worker.enqueue('send-email', {
    to: user.email,
    subject: 'Welcome!',
    body: 'Welcome to {{ .Project.Metadata.Name }}',
  });

  res.status(202).json({ jobId, status: 'queued' });
});

// Delayed job
router.post('/reports', async (req, res) => {
  const jobId = await worker.enqueue(
    'generate-report',
    { reportId: req.body.id, format: 'pdf' },
    { delayMs: 5000, priority: 1 },
  );

  res.status(202).json({ jobId });
});
```

### 5. Start/Stop Worker with Service

```typescript
import { createService } from '@ironplate/service';
import { worker } from './worker';

const service = await createService('{service}')
  .routes('/api', apiRouter)
  .build();

await service.start();
worker.start();

// On shutdown:
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
  worker.stop();
});
```

## Job Lifecycle

```
pending → running → completed
                  → failed (after maxRetries exhausted)
         → retrying → running → ...
```

## CRITICAL Rules
- `MemoryJobStore` is for development only — no persistence across restarts
- For production, implement `IJobStore` backed by Redis or PostgreSQL
- ALWAYS set `timeoutMs` on long-running jobs to prevent stuck workers
- ALWAYS check `ctx.signal.aborted` in long loops for graceful cancellation
- Use `priority` (lower = higher priority) for ordering
- ALWAYS stop the worker during graceful shutdown

## Checklist
- [ ] `@ironplate/jobs` dependency added
- [ ] Job definitions created with proper retry/timeout config
- [ ] JobWorker initialized with store and registered jobs
- [ ] API routes enqueue jobs (return 202 Accepted)
- [ ] Worker started after service starts
- [ ] Worker stopped during graceful shutdown
- [ ] Production job store planned (Redis/PostgreSQL)
